body:
Unfortunately, the data type being returned is json (see attached photo). 
I changed yii.js it to account for this oddity: 

```
if (options.dataType == 'jsonp' || options.dataType == 'json') {
   return;
}
```

then I overrode the Yii Asset with my version of yii.js. I don't know if this is worth changing as I don't know the unintended consequences (I'm going to continue and if something arises I'll address it then). 

Disclaimer: I haven't fully inspected gcal.js. I'm going to do that today.  

<img width="1097" alt="screen shot 2016-08-04 at 9 51 47 am" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/10386821/17404397/7a72ab42-5a29-11e6-87ba-ce4356c09717.png">

it was mentioned in the original issue report that this option was not possible for some reason:

> I noticed there is an option to set a "reloadable" list of scripts, but in my case, I have no control on it as the url is generated on the fly by fullcalendar's gcal plugin (except if I change plugin's code which is was I did to unlock the situation).

@airmoi any comments?

@Rjgoolsby as a workaround, I changed gcal's line 75 to append a timestamp to the base url : 
`var url = API_BASE + '/' + encodeURIComponent(sourceOptions.googleCalendarId) + '/events?callback=?&_=' + jQuery.now(); // jsonp`

For now it works, but this is not a confortable situation as this is a third party script I shouldn't have to edit
